title: Air Pollution Non-Attainment Areas, West Virginia, 2005
name: Air Pollution Non-Attainment Areas, West Virginia, 2005
description:
A non-attainment area is defined as any area where air pollution levels persistently exceed the national ambient air quality standards. EPA uses six "criteria pollutants" as indicators of air quality, and has established for each of them a maximum concentration above which adverse effects on human health may occur. These threshold concentrations are called National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS). 

In West Virginia, as of February 2008, five non-attainment areas exist for particulate matte with diameters of 2.5 micrometers or less. Current status can be viewed HERE. 

Particulate Matter (< 2.5 micrometers)
EPA has formally designated the following areas in West Virginia as nonattainment for the PM2.5 NAAQS effective April 5, 2005:

1. Charleston (Kanawha and Putnam Counties)
2. Huntington (Cabell and Wayne Counties and the Graham Tax District of Mason County)
3. Martinsburg (Berkeley County)
4. Parkersburg (Wood County and the Grant Tax District of Pleasants County)
5. Weirton (Brooke and Hancock Counties)
6. Wheeling (Marshall and Ohio Counties)

All other West Virginia counties are currently deemed to be attaining the PM 2.5 NAAQS and are designated as attainment areas or are unclassifiable. Source information from West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection's (WVDEP) Division of Air Quality (DWM). Non-attainment boundaries are designated via county and tax district boundaries. Therefore, the GIS coverage provided here is constructed of tax-district boundaries. GIS coverage published by WVGISTC in February 2008.

Data was uploaded as shp, dbf, shx into Geocommons.
